            <div n="1">
                <head>
                    <hi rendition="#k">Universal Diffusion of Life.</hi>
                </head>
                <p>&#x2014;When the active<lb break="yes"/>curiosity of man is engaged in
                    interrogating nature, or<lb break="yes"/>when his imagination dwells on the wide
                    fields of or-<lb break="no"/>ganic creation, among the multifarious
                        impressions<lb break="yes"/>which his mind receives, perhaps none is so
                    strong and<lb break="yes"/>profound as that of the universal profusion with
                        which<lb break="yes"/>life is every where distributed. Even on the polar
                        ice<lb break="yes"/>the air resounds with the cries or songs of birds,
                        and<lb break="yes"/>with the hum of insects. Nor is it only the lower
                        dense<lb break="yes"/>and vaporous strata of the atmosphere which are
                        thus<lb break="yes"/>filled with life, but also the higher and more
                        ethereal<lb break="yes"/>regions. Whenever Mont Blanc or the summits of
                        the<lb break="yes"/>Cordilleras have been ascended, living creatures have<lb
                        break="yes"/>been found there. On the Chimborazo, eight thousand<lb
                        break="yes"/>feet higher than Etna, we found butterflies and other<lb
                        break="yes"/>winged insects, borne by ascending currents of air to<lb
                        break="yes"/>those almost unapproachable solitudes, which man, led<lb
                        break="yes"/>by a restless curiosity or unappeasable thirst of know-<lb
                        break="no"/>ledge, treads with adventurous but cautious steps; like<lb
                        break="yes"/>him, strangers in those elevated regions, their presence<lb
                        break="yes"/>shows us that the more flexible organization of animal<lb
                        break="yes"/>creation can subsist far beyond the limits at which<lb
                        break="yes"/>vegetation ceases. The condor, the giant of the vulture<lb
                        break="yes"/>tribe, often soared over our heads above all the summits<lb
                        break="yes"/>of the Andes, at an altitude higher than would be the<lb
                        break="yes"/>Peak of Teneriffe if piled on the snow-covered crests<lb
                        break="yes"/>of the Pyrenees. The rapacity of this powerful bird<lb
                        break="yes"/>attracts him to these regions, whence his far-seeing eye<lb
                        break="yes"/>may discern the objects of his pursuit, the soft-woolled<lb
                        break="yes"/>vicunas, which, wandering in herds, frequent, like the<lb
                        break="yes"/>chamois, the mountain pastures adjacent to the regions<lb
                        break="yes"/>of perpetual snow.&#x2014;<hi rendition="#i">Humboldt.</hi>
                </p>
            </div>
